{"title_page": "Japanese postal mark", "text_new": "{{redirect|\u3012|the almost identical symbol used in Kazakhstan|Kazakhstani tenge}}\n{{Refimprove|date=December 2014}}\n[[File:Japanesezipcodemark.png|thumb|right|200px|Several versions of the \u3012 mark]]\n[[File:Japan Mailbox Red.jpg|thumb|A [[postbox]] in Japan]]\n[[File:Hijetcargo.jpg|thumb|A post van]]\n{{nihongo|'''\u3012'''|\u90f5\u4fbf\u8a18\u53f7|y\u016bbin kig\u014d}} is the [[service mark]] of [[Japan Post]] and its successor, [[Japan Post Holdings]], the [[postal operator]] in [[Japan]]. It is also used as a Japanese [[postal code]] mark since the introduction of the latter in 1968. The mark is a stylized [[katakana]] syllable ''te'' ([[\u30c6]]), from the word ''teishin'' (\u9013\u4fe1 communications). The mark was introduced on February 8th, 1887 (Meiji 20.2.8).\n<!-- Proper translation is needed.-->\n<!--\n== Chronological overview<ref>https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/\u90f5\u4fbf\u8a18\u53f7</ref> == \n\n1887.2.8 Communications Ministry Notification No. 11 (''Creation of Ministerial crest''): \"Hereafter, the \u201cT\u201d mark is to be used as ministerial crest in all departments\". \n\n1887.2.14 changed to \u3012.\n\n1887.2.19 ''Official Gazette'' \u5b98\u5831 repeats \"correct is \u3012\".\n\n- There are various suggestions why an alphabet \"T\" or chinese character \"\u4e01\" were considered unsuitable, probably for their ample usage in other already established contexts. \nThis was avoided by adding a second stroke over \"T\". The idea is attributed to the first-time Minister of Communications himself, ENOMOTO Takeaki \u698e\u672c\u6b66\u63da (1836-1908).\n\n1950 Ministry of Posts - \u90f5\u653f\u7701 (created in 1949, from parts of dissoluted Communications Ministry \u9013\u4fe1\u7701) notification No. 35 adopts the \u201c\u3012\u201d mark as postal flag etc.\n\n2001.1.15 The above two notifications are abolished with the reform of central government agencies.\n\n2001.1.19 The newly established Postal Service Department (\u90f5\u653f\u4e8b\u696d\u5e81) with notification No. 1 adopts \u3012 symbol as postal logo (notification dated Jan. 6 enforced Jan. 19).\n\n2003.2.7 The semi-privatized ''Japan Post Co.'' (\u65e5\u672c\u90f5\u653f\u516c\u793e)announces the continuation of \u3012 mark as \u201csymbol mark\u201d.\n\n2007.3.19 After the privatization, [[Japan Post Holdings]] announces the continuation of the \u3012 logo as \u201ccorporate brandmark\u201d.\n-->\n==Usage== \nTo indicate a postal code, the mark is written first, and the postal code is written after. For example, one area of [[Meguro, Tokyo]], would have <code>\u3012153-0061</code> written on any mail, in order to direct mail to that location. This usage has resulted in the inclusion of the mark into the [[Japanese language|Japanese]] [[Character encoding|character sets]] for [[computer]]s, and thus eventually their inclusion into [[Unicode]], where it can also be found on the Japanese Post Office emoji.<ref name=\"emojipedia\">{{vcite web | title=Japanese Post Office | url=http://emojipedia.org/japanese-post-office/ | publisher=Emojipedia | accessdate=2014-10-05}}</ref> In most keyboard-based [[Japanese IME|Japanese input systems]], it can be created by typing \"yuubin\" and then doing a [[Japanese IME#Kana to kanji conversion|kanji conversion]].\n\nOf the versions shown to the right, the one on the far right is the standard mark used in addressing. The circled y\u016bbin mark in the middle is often used on maps to denote post offices.\n\n{{clear}}\n== Encoding{{anchor|Unicode}} ==\nThe postal mark appears in the following [[Unicode]] characters. Before the introduction of Unicode, the simple postal mark was encoded for Japanese use in [[JIS X 0208]] (including the [[Shift JIS]] encoding). A stylised version in the form of a face was included in some vendor variants of [[Shift JIS]], including the KanjiTalk 7 variant of [[MacJapanese]], and become part of a standardised Shift JIS variant (at a different location) with the 2000 release of [[JIS X 0213]]. The Japanese broadcasting standard [[ARIB STD-B24]] also included two variants amongst its extensions to JIS X 0208 for use as map symbols: a duplicate of the simple mark, and a circled variant. Earlier [[KPS 9566]] editions included both the simple postal mark and a version in a downward-pointing triangle,<ref>{{citation|mode=cs1 |url=https://unicode.org/wg2/docs/n2374.pdf |title=Proposal to add of 70 symbols to ISO/IEC 10646-1:2000 |date=2001-09-03 |author=Committee for Standardization of the D P R of Korea (CSK) |id=[[ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 2]]/WG 2 N2374}}</ref><ref>{{cite iso-ir |number=202 |date=1998-06-22 |title=DPRK Standard Korean Graphic Character Set for Information Interchange |sponsor=Committee for Standardization of D. P. R. of Korea}}</ref> but the latter was removed in 2003.<ref>{{citation|mode=cs1 |url=https://unicode.org/Public/MAPPINGS/VENDORS/MISC/KPS9566.TXT |title=KPS 9566-2003 to Unicode |author=Unicode Consortium |author-link=Unicode Consortium |date=2011-04-27}}</ref>\n\n[[Emoji]] sets from Japanese cellular carriers included a building with a prominently displayed postal mark (in the simplest case, a postal mark enclosed within a building outline) as a pictograph for a [[post office]]; this was also adopted into Unicode in version 6.0. Earlier versions of [[Segoe#Variations|Segoe UI Emoji]] prior to [[Windows 10 Anniversary Update]] simplified this emoji, showing it as a red postal mark.<ref name=\"emojipedia\" />\n{{charmap\n|3012|name1=Postal Mark\n|3020|name2=Postal Mark Face\n|3036|name3=Circled Postal Mark\n|1F3E3|name4=Japanese Post Office\n\n|map1=7-bit [[JIS X 0208]]\n|map1char1=22 29\n\n|map2=7-bit JIS ([[au by KDDI]] and others)<ref name=\"utcL210132\">{{cite web |url=https://www.unicode.org/L2/L2010/10132-emojidata.pdf |id=UTC L2/10-132 |title=Emoji Symbols: Background Data\u2014Background data for Proposal for Encoding Emoji Symbols |first1=Markus |last1=Scherer |first2=Mark |last2=Davis |first3=Kat |last3=Momoi |first4=Darick |last4=Tong |first5=Yasuo |last5=Kida |first6=Peter |last6=Edberg}}</ref>\n|map2char1=22 29\n|map2char4=79 32\n\n|map3=7-bit JIS ([[ARIB STD B24 character set|ARIB]])\n|map3char1=7b 28 <!-- 7b 28 and 22 29 are duplicates? -->\n|map3char3=7D 2F\n\n|map4=[[Shift JIS]] ([[MacJapanese|Apple KanjiTalk 7]])<ref name=\"macjapanese\">{{cite web |url=https://unicode.org/Public/MAPPINGS/VENDORS/APPLE/JAPANESE.TXT |title=Map (external version) from Mac OS Japanese encoding to Unicode 2.1 and later. |author=Apple, Inc |author-link=Apple, Inc |publisher=[[Unicode Consortium]] |date=2005-04-05}}</ref>\n|map4char1=81 A7\n|map4char2=86 b3\n\n|map5=Shift JIS ([[JIS X 0213]])<ref>{{citation|mode=cs1 |url=http://x0213.org/codetable/sjis-0213-2004-with-char-u8.txt |title=Shift_JIS-2004 (JIS X 0213:2004 Appendix 1) vs Unicode mapping table |author=Project X0213 |date=2013-03-30}}</ref>\n|map5char1=81 A7\n|map5char2=83 E4\n\n|map6=Shift JIS ([[au by KDDI]])<ref name=\"EmojiSrc\">{{cite web |url=https://www.unicode.org/Public/UCD/latest/ucd/EmojiSources.txt |title=Emoji Sources |work=Unicode Character Database |author=Unicode Consortium |author-link=Unicode Consortium}}</ref>\n|map6char1=81 a7\n|map6char4=f3 51\n\n|map7=Shift JIS ([[DoCoMo]])<ref name=\"EmojiSrc\" />\n|map7char1=81 a7\n|map7char4=f8 c6\n\n|map8=Shift JIS ([[SoftBank Mobile|SoftBank 3G]])<ref name=\"EmojiSrc\" />\n|map8char1=81 a7\n|map8char4=f7 94\n\n|map9=Shift JIS ([[ARIB STD B24 character set|ARIB]])<ref>{{cite web |url=https://github.com/google/emoji4unicode/blob/master/data/arib/arib.ucm |title=ARIB Broadcast Symbols Unicode conversion mapping table using ICU's .ucm file format and representing ARIB codes in the Shift-JIS encoding scheme. |first=Markus |last=Scherer |publisher=[[Google]] |date=2008}}</ref>\n|map9char1=ee 47 <!-- ee 47 and 81 a7 are duplicates? -->\n|map9char3=ef 4e\n\n|map10=[[EUC-JP]] ([[JIS X 0213]])<ref>{{citation